The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                               BRIEFS
                  
	Calcutta, Jan. 25: A man whipped out a revolver and fired in the air during a brawl after his Tata Indica collided with a taxi on north Calcuttas Galiff Street tonight.    
	Rajesh Sana, a businessman in his late 30s who was returning from a wedding with his wife, apparently fired out of nervousness after the taxi driver demanded a hefty compensation, police said. The couple had fled but the police traced and arrested Rajesh from the car number provided by witnesses.         
	Calcutta: The Bengal government will implement the UGC pay panels recommendations, the finance minister said on Sunday. The salaries of nearly 15,000 college and university teachers will go up.         
	Behrampore: Three men were killed in Bengals Nadia district, apparently because drivers were blinded by fog. A truck hit a stationary lorry on National Highway 34 in Dhubulia, killing two cleaners. On the same highway, in Kalyani, a cyclist was run over. In Murshidabad, 24 people were injured when a bus drove into a ditch.         
	Calcutta: A tiger caged on the fringes of a Sunderbans village was released in the wild on Sunday. Forest officials said they had set the trap after pug marks were seen repeatedly near Deulbari village, about 150km from Calcutta.        
	Durgapur: Burglars broke into two jewellery shops in Ranigunj town, 230km from Calcutta, on Saturday and took away Rs 14 lakh in cash and ornaments. The theft was detected on Sunday.                                                                                                                                                                        
